If you want to upgrade from an older version, you can first update the files in your self-hosted cloud, then execute the command in the "Hazy Methods with Official Version Installed" section, and finally upgrade in the main control backend.

Cloud node monitoring function description:

By default, monitoring uses the cloud server to request CDN nodes, so it's essential to maintain a stable network connection between the cloud server and the CDN nodes. Additionally, if using a control panel like BT Panel, do not install the bt_safe extension in PHP; otherwise, TCP-type monitoring will not be possible. For ping-type monitoring, the exec function must also be enabled.
It supports multi-node monitoring (just like the official version). To add other monitoring nodes, you can edit the config.php configuration file and add them according to the comments.

Modify to your own installed node, or use the default GitHub node for installation.
/opt/cdnfly/master/panel/src/views/system/update/index.html


The main control login address is: http://main control IP/
Administrator username and password: admin/cdnfly
Regular user account and password: jason/cdnfly

Server configuration requirements

Main controller
1. Memory - Since Elasticsearch is installed on the controller, 16GB or more is recommended. If the website has low traffic, 8GB is also acceptable, but at least 4GB is recommended.
2. Hard Drive - Solid State Drive (SSD) is recommended. Also consider the access log size; 100GB or more is recommended, but smaller amounts are fine.
3. CPU - CPU with at least 2 cores
4. Open ports 80, 88, and 9200.
node

1. Memory - at least 2GB or more
2. Hard Disk - Configure according to the website cache size
3. CPU - Nginx primarily runs on the CPU, so for better access performance, the CPU should be as powerful as possible.
4. Open port 80 443 5000
system
Supports CentOS 7 to Ubuntu 16.04

Latest official public information
Dear cdnfly user:
A login security vulnerability has been discovered and needs to be temporarily patched using the following method: Find a domain that only you know, and use this domain for administrator login.
For example, use a domain name without http://, and follow the path: System Management ---> System Settings ---> User Related. Restrict administrators to log in only from this domain.


Relocation of main control
Note: The migration steps below do not include migrating Elasticsearch data.
1. Back up the old controller data
Execute the following command on the old master controller to start the backup (Note: The old master controller's processes will be stopped before the backup is performed).

cd /root
curl http://us.centos.bz/cdnfly/backup_master.sh -o backup_master.sh
chmod +x backup_master.sh
./backup_master.sh
At this point, a file named cdn.sql.gz will be generated in the /root directory. Please transfer this file to the /root/ directory of the new master controller. You can use the scp command, as follows:

cd /root
scp cdn.sql.gz root@newmasterIP:/root/
2. Install the main control program on the new machine.
First, log in to cdnfly.cn, update the authorization to the new master control IP, and clear the machine code.
Log in to the old master control machine and execute the following command to check the version:

grep VERSION_NAME /opt/cdnfly/master/conf/config.py
As shown in the image below, the version is v4.1.6:

Log in to the new machine and execute the following command to install:

curl http://dl.cdnfly.cn/cdnfly/master.sh -o master.sh
chmod +x master.sh
./master.sh --ver v4.1.60
Replace v4.1.60 with your own main controller version number.
3. Log in to the new main controller and restore the backup.
Execute the following command to restore

cd /root
curl http://us.centos.bz/cdnfly/restore_master.sh -o restore_master.sh
chmod +x restore_master.sh
./restore_master.sh
Download the file `/opt/cdnfly/master/conf/config.py` from the old master controller and upload it to the new master controller to overwrite the existing one.
Then initialize Elasticsearch on the new master controller and restart the new master controller.
Execute the following command to initialize:

cd /tmp
wget us.centos.bz/cdnfly/int_es.sh -O int_es.sh
chmod +x int_es.sh
./int_es.sh /home/es
supervisorctl restart all
The `/var/lib/elasticsearch` directory is the Elasticsearch data directory, which can be changed to other directories, such as `/home/es`.

4. Replace the master IP in the node.
Log in to each node one by one and execute the following command to replace...

new_master_ip="Replace this with the new master IP address"
sed -i "s/ES_IP =.*/ES_IP = \"$new_master_ip\"/" /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/config.py
sed -i "s/MASTER_IP.*/MASTER_IP = \"$new_master_ip\"/g" /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/config.py
sed -i "s/hosts:.*/hosts: [\"$new_master_ip:9200\"]/" /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/filebeat.yml
logs_path=`awk '/error_log/{print $2}' /usr/local/openresty/nginx/conf/nginx.conf | sed 's/error.log//'`
if [[ `echo $logs_path | grep ^/ ` != "" ]];then
    sed -i "s#.*access.log# - $logs_path/access.log#" /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/filebeat.yml
    sed -i "s#.*stream.log# - $logs_path/stream.log#" /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/filebeat.yml
fi
sed -i "s#http://.*:88#http://$new_master_ip:88#" /usr/local/openresty/nginx/conf/listen_80.conf /usr/local/openresty/nginx/conf/listen_other.conf
ps aux | grep [/]usr/local/openresty/nginx/sbin/nginx | ​​awk '{print $2}' | xargs kill -HUP || true
supervisorctl restart filebeat
supervisorctl restart agent
supervisorctl restart task

After the master controller changes its IP address, the node can be modified using the following commands.

new_master_ip="Replace this with the master IP address"
(Check the es_pwd password in the backend system upgrade)
es_pwd="Replace this with your es password"

sed -i "s/ES_IP =.*/ES_IP = \"$new_master_ip\"/" /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/config.py

sed -i "s/MASTER_IP.*/MASTER_IP = \"$new_master_ip\"/g" /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/config.py

sed -i "s/hosts:.*/hosts: [\"$new_master_ip:9200\"]/" /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/filebeat.yml

chattr -i /usr/local/openresty/nginx/conf/ /usr/local/openresty/nginx/conf/listen_80.conf /usr/local/openresty/nginx/conf/listen_other.conf

sed -i "s#http://.*:88#http://$new_master_ip:88#" /usr/local/openresty/nginx/conf/listen_80.conf /usr/local/openresty/nginx/conf/listen_other.conf

chattr +i /usr/local/openresty/nginx/conf/ /usr/local/openresty/nginx/conf/listen_80.conf /usr/local/openresty/nginx/conf/listen_other.conf

sed -i "s/ES_PWD =.*/ES_PWD = \"$es_pwd\"/" /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/config.py

sed -i "s/password:.*/password: \"$es_pwd\"/" /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/filebeat.yml

sed -i "s/agent-pwd:.*/agent-pwd: \"$es_pwd\"/" /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/filebeat.yml

ps aux | grep [/]usr/local/openresty/nginx/sbin/nginx | ​​awk '{print $2}' | xargs kill -HUP || true

supervisorctl -c /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/supervisord.conf restart filebeat

supervisorctl -c /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/supervisord.conf restart agent

supervisorctl -c /opt/cdnfly/agent/conf/supervisord.conf restart task
